# Engineering Quality Rules

Apply these rules generically regardless of language, framework, or architecture:

- keep transport layers thin
- keep business logic out of UI/presentation layers
- keep persistence logic in dedicated persistence ownership
- keep shared domain concepts defined once and reused consistently
- do not leave reusable types, interfaces, enums, constants, schemas, policy maps, event names, or large config objects inline in logic-heavy or presentation-heavy files
- wrap important third-party libraries behind local common modules, adapters, gateways, utilities, or shared UI components
- document shared/common modules so future work reuses them instead of bypassing them
- keep methods small, reviewable, and explicit
- extract validation, transformation, mapping, policy logic, and branch-heavy logic into named helpers or dedicated modules when it improves ownership and readability
- never leak secrets, tokens, credentials, or protected data
- validate input at trust boundaries
- make async workflows observable, bounded, and failure-aware
- write tests for changed behavior
- update documentation in the same delivery stream as behavior changes
- measure coverage on touched modules, not only global averages

Required validation mindset:

- do not trust a passing happy path alone
- do not trust isolated unit tests as the whole story
- validate negative paths, boundaries, permissions, state transitions, and regressions
- keep automated tests deterministic where practical
- use repeatable QA evidence or harnesses for meaningful workflows

Whenever a permanent engineering or quality rule changes, update `claude.md`.
